n of the state, increasing public violence, and the "globalization" of Guatemalan national politics have undermined the traditional ties of kinship, custom, and belief that gave Guatemalans a sense of identity, and many are turning to Protestantism to recreate a sense of order, identity, and belonging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGuatemala - Church history - 20th century. 0aProtestant churcheszGuatemalaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72816540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292761421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292761421/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK